{{NHS-stub}}

The '''International Classification of External Causes of Injury''' (ICECI) is a [[medical classification]] providing codes for external [[injury|injuries]]. It is designed to aid professionals and researchers in the statistical tracking and prevention of injury. <ref>[http://www.iceci.org/ ICECI Website]</ref>

First released in 2001, the ICECI is a Related Classification in the [[World_Health_Organization|WHO]] Family of International Classifications (WHO-FIC). It is related to [[ICD-10]] [[ICD-10_Chapter_XX:_External_causes_of_morbidity_and_mortality|Chapter XX]] (External causes of morbidity and mortality). While the ICD-10 classifies injuries in and of themselves, the ICECI allows for systematic description of the causes and circumstances surrounding the injury. <ref>[http://www.who.int/classifications/icd/adaptations/iceci/en/index.html WHO | International Classification of External Causes of Injury (ICECI)]</ref>

