{{Disease-stub}}

A '''risk panel''' is a body that determines whether a person's mental illness causes them to be too much of a risk to society to be released from [[involuntary commitment]]. In the United States, the members of a risk panel may consist of medical officers appointed by the warden or superintendent of an institution, the [[U.S. Attorney General]], and the [[United States Public Health Service]]. The [[Food and Drug Administration]] also has a risk panel, a 15-member advisory panel to educate consumers about the risks and benefits of drugs, devices and vaccines.<ref>http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa5351/is_200203/ai_n21310836/</ref>
